      "size": "14\" x 5\"",
      "shell": "Aluminum",
      "description": "The Ludwig Acrolite was one of the most ubiquitous snare drums in American music by the mid-1980s — a budget-to-mid-range aluminum shell snare that had been in continuous production since the 1960s. Its selection for \"Darkness Descends\" was pragmatic: Hoglan needed a snare that would crack with authority at the speeds he was executing, and the Acrolite's aluminum shell delivered exactly that character.\n\nAluminum shells produce a bright, cutting sound with fast response — different from the warmth of steel or the complexity of brass. For a 19-year-old playing at 247 BPM, response speed mattered. The Acrolite's shallow 5\" depth kept the snare wire tension manageable at extreme velocities, maintaining a consistent \"crack\" character rather than the smeared attack that deeper, more resonant drums can produce at high speed.\n\nHoglan tuned the Acrolite medium-high for the Darkness Descends sessions — a tension setting that maximized the aluminum shell's natural brightness while maintaining enough body to stand out in Metoyer's dense production. The snare sound on this album is one of its defining characteristics: sharp, precise, almost military in its articulation, driving patterns that could have devolved into noise and keeping them legible.\n\nThe choice of an Acrolite rather than a more expensive boutique drum reflects the realities of a Combat Records thrash band in 1986. Gene Hoglan was not yet an endorser with free equipment; he used what worked. That the Acrolite worked as well as it did on this recording is a testament to both the drum's inherent quality and Hoglan's ability to extract maximum character from his tools.",
